{"parse":{"title":"wood","pageid":4648,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Wood}}\n==English==\n[[File:Popular American Furniture Wood Types.jpg|thumb|Varieties of '''wood''' (sense 2).]]\n{{wp}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|en|substance}}{{PIE word|en|dwóh₁}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰeh₁-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|wode}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wudu}}, {{m|ang|widu||wood, forest, grove; tree; timber}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*widu}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*widuz||wood}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₁weydʰh₁-||to separate}}. The spelling developed as it did in {{m|en|wool}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|nl|wede|t=wood, twig}}, {{cog|gmh|wite|t=wood}}, {{cog|da,nb,nn,sv|ved|t=wood}}, {{cog|ovd|wið|t=wood, timber}}, {{cog|fo,is|viður|t=wood}}, {{cog|nn|ved|t=wood, firewood}}, {{m|nn|vid|t=wide, broad}}. Further cognates include {{cog|ga|fiodh||t=a wood, tree}}, {{cog|ga|fid||t=tree}} and {{cog|cy|gwŷdd||t=trees}}, from {{cog|cel-pro|*widus||t=wood}}. Unrelated to {{noncog|nl|woud|t=forest}}, {{noncog|de|Wald|t=forest}} (see {{noncog|en|wold}}).\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|wo͝od|a=RP,AusE,GenAm}}, {{IPA|en|/wʊd/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-au-wood.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/wɵd/|a=SSB}}\n* {{IPA|en|/wʉd/|a=Scotland,NI}}\n* {{IPA|en|/(ʋ)ʊɖ/|a=Indic}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʊd|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|would}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q287}}{{lb|en|uncountable}} The substance making up the central part of the [[trunk]] and [[branches]] of a [[tree]]. Used as a material for construction, to manufacture various items, etc. or as fuel.\n#: {{ux|en|This table is made of '''wood'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There was lots of '''wood''' on the beach.}}\n#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=X|lines=1006–11|passage=O that men&nbsp;/ (Canſt thou believe&#8239;?) ſhould be ſo ſtupid grown,&nbsp;/ While yet the Patriark liv’d, who ſcap’d the Flood,&nbsp;/ As to forſake the living God, and fall&nbsp;/ To worſhip thir own work in '''Wood''' and Stone&nbsp;/ For Gods&#8239;!|year=1873}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|chapter=Foreword|passage=He stood transfixed before the unaccustomed view of London at night time, a vast panorama which reminded him {{...}} of some '''wood''' engravings far off and magical, in a printshop in his childhood.}}\n# {{senseid|en|wood from a particular species of tree}} {{lb|en|countable}} The wood from a particular species of tree.\n#: {{ux|en|Teak is much used for outdoor benches, but a number of other '''woods''' are also suitable, such as [[ipé]], [[redwood]], etc.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Walls and Ceilings|editor=Robert M. Jones|ISBN=0809434520| year=1980| publisher=Time-Life Books| page=93| passage=A few '''woods''', such as cedar and redwood, are prized for their rugged naturalness and they age so beautifully that they are generally left unfinished.}}\n# {{senseid|en|forested or wooded area}} {{lb|en|countable|often|as [[plurale tantum]]}} A forested or [[wooded]] area.\n#: {{synonyms|en|woods|forest|woodland|Thesaurus:forest}}\n#: {{ux|en|A '''wood''' beyond this moor was viewed as a border area in the seventeenth century.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He got lost in the '''woods''' beyond Seattle.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|act=IV|scene=i|page=144|column=2|lines=92–94|passage=''Macbeth'' ſhall neuer vanquiſh’d be, vntill&nbsp;/ Great Byrnam '''Wood''', to high Dunſmane Hill&nbsp;/ Shall come againſt him.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1845|author={{w|Hans Christian Andersen}}|translator=Mary Howitt|title=Only a Fiddler! and O.T.|location=London|publisher=Richard Bentley|chapter=|volume=II|page=298|text=“There upon the hill, close by the '''wood''', did I act the elf-maiden,” said Sophie.}}\n# [[firewood|Firewood]].\n#: {{ux|en|We need more '''wood''' for the fire.}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=8|passage=We toted in the '''wood''' and got the fire going nice and comfortable. Lord James still set in one of the chairs and Applegate had cabbaged the other and was hugging the stove.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=July-August|author=w:Henry Petroski\n|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/2013/4/geothermal-energy Geothermal Energy]\n|volume=101|issue=4|magazine=w:American Scientist\n|passage=Energy has seldom been found where we need it when we want it. Ancient nomads, wishing to ward off the evening chill and enjoy a meal around a campfire, had to collect '''wood''' and then spend time and effort coaxing the heat of friction out from between sticks to kindle a flame.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|golf}} A type of [[golf club]], the [[head]] of which was traditionally made of wood.\n# {{lb|en|music}} A [[woodwind]] instrument.\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|slang}} An [[erection]] of the [[penis]].\n#: {{ux|en|That girl at the strip club gave me '''wood'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|chess|uncountable|slang}} Chess pieces.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1971|title=Chess Life & Review|volume=26|page=309\n|passage={{...}} White has nothing but a lot of frozen '''wood''' on the board while Black operates on the Q-side.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* In the sense of ''a forested area'', the singular generally refers to a discrete area of forest, while the plural is often used when a more vaguely defined area is meant. For the sense of ''woodwind instrument'', {{m|en|wind}} is the more common shortening.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|substance}} {{l|en|timber}}\n* {{sense|wooded area, US}} {{l|en|wood lot}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|wood cookie|wood spurge|Australian wood cockroach|brezel wood|wood acid\n|crabwood|Abbey Wood|Wood Creek|wood-bill|lay the wood\n|alderwood||stress wood|wood fox|Wood-Ridge\n|algumwood|citron wood\n|[[aloeswood]] ({{taxfmt|Aquilaria malaccensis|species}})\n|applewood|wood lily\n|[[arrowwood]] ({{taxfmt|Viburnum|genus}} spp.)\n|Ashurst Wood\n|ashwood|candle-wood|fairway wood|Mediterranean wood|three wood|wood buttercup|wood goldilocks\n|babe in the woods|bishop wood|wood hoopoe|wood thrush\n|backwood\n|backwoods\n|balsawood|bow-wood\n|[[barwood]] ({{taxlink|Baphia nitida|species}})\n|basketwood|camp wood\n|[[basswood]] ({{taxfmt|Tilia|genus}} spp.)\n|beechwood\n|beefwood| wound wood\n|bentwood|aguila wood|wood avens|wood bedstraw|wood owl|wood vetch\n|birchwood\n|bitterwood\n|blackwood\n|Blackwood\n|[[bloodwood]] ({{taxfmt|Haematoxylum campechianum|species}})\n|bogwood|rotten wood|wood millet\n|[[boxwood]] ({{taxfmt|Buxus|genus}} spp., especially {{taxfmt|Buxus sempervirens|species}})\n|[[brazilwood]] ({{taxlink|Caesalpinia echinata|species}})\n|Bretton Woods\n|[[briarwood]] ({{taxfmt|Erica arborea|species}})\n|browsewood\n|brushwood| Wood Wood\n|bugwood ({{taxlink|Acacia verticillata|species}}, etc)\n|bulletwood\n|burlwood\n|buttonwood|caustic wood alkali|wood fretter\n|[[campeachy wood]], {{vern|Campeche wood}} ({{taxfmt|Haematoxylum campechianum|species}})\n|camphorwood\n|[[candlewood]] ({{taxfmt|Fouquieria splendens|species}})\n|Cannock Wood\n|canoewood\n|carrotwood\n|cassava wood\n|cedarwood\n|chatwood\n|cheesewood\n|Chelmsley Wood\n|cherrywood\n|chicken of the woods\n|citronwood\n|Cliffe Woods\n|coachwood\n|cocuswood\n|Colliers Wood\n|copsewood\n|cordwood\n|cottonwood\n|dead wood\n|deadwood\n|Deadwood\n|dealwood\n|devilwood\n|does a bear shit in the woods\n|does the Pope shit in the woods\n|[[dogwood]] (''{{ll|mul|Cornus}}'' spp. etc.)\n|driftwood\n|dyewood\n|earlywood\n|Eastwood\n|elfin wood\n|elkwood\n|elmwood\n|fatwood\n|featherwood\n|fibrewood\n|fiddlewood\n|firewood\n|firwood\n|flavorwood\n|flintwood\n|fruitwood\n|fuelwood\n|giltwood\n|gopher wood\n|greasewood\n|greenwood\n|groundwood\n|Hadley Wood\n|Hall i' th' Wood\n|Handsworth Wood\n|hardwood\n|harewood\n|Harold Wood\n|Harper Woods\n|hazelwood\n|heartwood\n|[[hen of the woods]] ({{taxlink|Grifola frondosa|species}})\n|Hinchley Wood\n|Hollywood\n|Holme Wood\n|Holywood\n|horsewood\n|inkwood\n|inwood\n|Ireland Wood\n|ironwood\n|jackwood\n|jarrahwood\n|kidneywood\n|kindlewood\n|kingwood\n|knock on wood\n|lacewood\n|lancewood\n|latewood\n|leadwood\n|leatherwood\n|lemonwood\n|