ranslation_fixing]] -->\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|лес|m}}\n* Sanskrit: {{tt+|sa|वन|n}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|bosque|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|skog|c}}\n* Tajik: {{tt+|tg|беша}}, {{tt+|tg|ҷангал}}\n* Tocharian B: {{tt|txb|wartto}}, {{tt|txb|karāś}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{tt|ota|اورمان|tr=orman}}, {{t|ota|میشه|tr=meşe}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|ліс}}\n* Venetan: {{tt|vec|bosco|m}}, {{tt+|vec|bòsch|m}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t|wyi|kalk}}\n* Zulu: {{tt+|zu|ihlathi|c5|c6}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-see|firewood|firewood}}\n* Basque: {{tt|eu|egur}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|дърва́|p}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|llenya|f}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|dřevo|n}}, {{tt+|cs|dříví|n}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|hout}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puu|p|alt=puut}}, {{tt+|fi|polttopuu}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|bois de chauffage|m}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|leña|f}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|შეშა}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Holz|n}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|ξύλα|n-p}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|viður|m}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|kayu bakar}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt|ia|ligno}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|legna|f}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|땔나무}}\n* Ladin: {{tt|lld|leniam|m}}, {{tt|lld|lënia|f}}, {{tt|lld|lënia da tizé|f}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|līgnum}}\n* Latvian: {{tt+|lv|malka|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|дрво за огрев|n}}\n* Nepali: {{tt+|ne|दाउरा|tr=dāurā}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt+|no|ved|m}}\n* Occitan: {{tt+|oc|lenha|f}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|هیزم|tr=hizom}}, {{tt+|fa|هیمه|tr=hima}}\n* Polish: {{tt|pl|drewno opałowe|n}}, {{tt|pl|drewno na opał|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|lenha|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|дрова́|p}}\n* Sicilian: {{tt+|scn|ligna|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|leña|f}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|ved|c}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{tt|tpi|paiawut}}, {{tt+|tpi|diwai}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|odun}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|اوطون|tr=odun}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|дро́ва}}\n* Venetan: {{tt|vec|legne|f-p}}\n* Zulu: {{tt|zu|ukhuni|c11|c10}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|type of golf club}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|fusta|f}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|dřevo|n}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puu}}, {{tt|fi|puumaila}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Holz|n}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|tré|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|music: woodwind instrument}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|духов инструмент|m}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|dřeva|n-p}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puupuhallin}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|legni|m-p}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|slang: an erection}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|надървяне|n}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|stondis}}, {{tt+|fi|kanki}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Latte|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt+|mk|дрво|n}}, {{tt|mk|стап|m}}, {{tt|mk|ша́тор|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|tusa|f}}, {{tt+|pt|tesão|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|стоя́к|m}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt|zza|qazığ}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Old English: {{t-check|ang|wudu}} (1,2,3)\n* Telugu: {{t-check|te|చిట్టడవి}} (1), {{t+check|te|కలప}} (2)\n* Woiwurrung: {{t-check|wyi|kalk}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col3|en\n|firth\n|grove\n|holt\n|hurst\n|shaw\n|thicket\n|tree\n|wald\n|weald\n|wold\n|woods\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|wooden}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|srn|udu}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cover or plant with trees.\n#* '''1542''', [[w:Richard Devereux (died 1547)|Sir Richard Devereux]], letter, in ''Bibliotheca Topographica Britannica'', London: J. Nichols, published 1792, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6b9zJAIC0bEC&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194 page 155]:\n#*: Their be ii good bellys, a chales, and a few veſtments of litil valure, the ſtuff beſide is not worth xl s. lead ther ys non except in ii gutters the which the p’or hath convey’d in to ye town, but that is ſuar yt is metely '''wodey’d''' in hege rowys.\n# {{lb|en|reflexive|intransitive}} To hide behind trees.\n#* {{circa|1586}}, [[w:Ralph Lane|Sir Ralph Lane]], “Lane’s Account of the Englishmen Left in Virginia”, in {{w|Henry Sweetser Burrage}}, editor, ''Early English and French Voyages: Chiefly from Hakluyt, 1534–1608'', New York: Charles Scribner’s Sons, published 1906, [https://books.google.com/books?id=_yhAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA256 page 246]:\n#*: Immediatly, the other boate lying ready with their shot to skoure the place for our hand weapons to lande upon, which was presently done, although the land was very high and steepe, the Savages forthwith quitted the shoare, and betooke themselves to flight: wee landed, and having faire and easily followed for a smal time after them, who had '''wooded''' themselves we know not where {{...}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To supply with wood, or get supplies of wood for.\n#: ''to '''wood''' a steamboat or a locomotive''\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=1891-11|author=w:John Bidwell|editor=w:Josiah Gilbert Holland; w:Richard Watson Gilder| title=The First Emigrant Train to California| work=w:The Century Magazine| volume=XLI| issue=1| publisher=Scribner & Company| page=106| pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZIdIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106| passage=Many passengers would save a little by helping to “'''wood''' the boat,” ''i. e.,'' by carrying wood down the bank and throwing it on the boat, a special ticket being issued on that condition. }}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take or get a [[supply]] of wood.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Captain John Smith|year=c. 1629|chapter=XXVII|title=The True Travels, Adventures, and Observations of Captain John Smith| volume=II| location=London| publisher=Awnsham and John Churchill| year_published=1704| page=409| pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/truetravelsadven00smit#page/409| passage=In this little Iſle of ''Mevis,'' more than twenty Years ago, I have remained a great time together, to '''Wood''' and Water and refreſh my Men {{...}}}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to cover or plant with trees}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|залеся́вам}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|bebossen}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|metsittää}}, {{tt|fi|[[istuttaa]] [[metsä|metsää]]}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|aufforsten}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|rimboschire}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|пошумува}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|florestar}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|forestar}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|en|mad}}\nFrom {{der|en|enm|wood}}, from {{der|en|ang|wōd||mad, insane}}. See the full etymology at '''{{l|en|wode}}'''.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|wode}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj|er}}\n\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} [[mad|Mad]], [[insane]], [[crazed]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1593|author=w:Thomas Nashe|title=w:The Choice of Valentines|lines=140-141|passage=And then he flue on hir as he were '''wood''', / And on hir breeche did hack and foyne a-good.}}\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|5|9|passage=And like a lion '''wood''' amongst them fares, <br>Dealing his dreadfull blowes with large dispence}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|act=IV|scene=vii|page=114|column=1|passage=How the young whelpe of ''Talbots'' raging '''wood,'''&nbsp;/ Did [[flesh#Verb|fleſh]] his punie-ſword in Frenchmens blood.}}\n#* {{RQ:Eddison Worm|page=27|passage=A fearsome sight it was to behold how he swelled in his wrath, and his eyes blazed like disastrous stars at midnight, and being '''wood''' with anger he gnashed his teeth till the froth stood at his lips and slavered down his chin.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|wood-wroth}}\n* {{l|en|woodness}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|attributive|sylvan}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|lignario}}, {{t|es|maderero}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{etymid|en|peckerwood}}\n{{back-form|en|peckerwood}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|US|sometimes|_|offensive|chiefly|prison slang|of a person}} A [[peckerwood]].\n#* '''1991''', Mary E. Pelz, James W. Marquart and Terry Pelz, \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20101213143956/http://brokenchains.us/documents/abt1.pdf Right-Wing Extremism in the Texas Prisons: The Rise and Fall of the Aryan Brotherhood of Texas]\", ''The Prison Journal'', Winter-Fall 1991:\n#*: He further stated that \"I can't remember ever seeing a '''wood''' [white inmate] assault a nigger without being provoked\".\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2009|author=Brendan Joel Kelly|chapter=Pride vs. Power|chapterurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720171716/http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2009-05-14/calendar/pride-vs-power/|title=The Phoenix New Times\n|passage=Other than shout-outs to fellow \"'''woods''',\" I found no references on their record to racism, and after getting to know the members, I think Woodpile's message is the opposite of what the L.A. Times construed it to be — they want to bring hardcore white guys to rap music, rather than alienating anyone of any race.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Christian Workman|title=Black Boxed: Coming of Age Behind Prison Walls|passage=The only thing is, even though there are ways to remain neutral, to just be a '''wood''' and not get caught up in the white supremacist gang stuff, you do have to take a side if things get bad.}}\n\n{{cln|en|ethnic slurs|terms with open-syllable lengthening of Middle English /i u/}}\n{{C|en|Genitalia|Woods}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Adjective===\n{{enm-adj}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|wode|id=mad|t=mad, insane, crazy}}"}}